Prosper Loan Analysis¶

Dataset Structure¶

The project centers on a dataset obtained from Prosper a lending platform in America. The dataset contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan observations. Such variables include Loan Status, Prosper Rating, Prosper Score, Employmetn STtaus, Borrower APR & Rate etc.

Investigative Overview¶

As a practicing Credit Officer in a Microfinance Bank, I decided to understand the relationship between various variables in the dataet. I vhose variables such as Employment Status, Income Range, Term of Loan, Debt to Income Ratio and how those characteristics affected or the relationship with Borrower APR, Loan Status and Prosper Rating.

Distribution of Term¶

Prosper specialized in giving longer termed loans as shown from the plot above The 36 month tenor facility had the highest with more than double of the 10 year loans and about 10 times of the shorter one year loan tenor

Loan Status¶

About two third of Prosper Loan portfolio is still currently running and not defaulting 23.2% has been completed while 6.4% has been written off which would impact the Capital of the Bank depending on Regulatory ratios Almost 3% are in default of different day periods which should not be allowed to continue as those are the oans that tend to be chargedoff later

Distribution of Borrower APR¶

Borrower APR Distribution is also multi modal with various peaks at 0.17, 0.21 and at 0.36

Distribution of ProsperRating Alpha¶

Most loans were rated average or in the middle, neither high nor low Very few loans were give the highest rating of AA

<AxesSubplot:xlabel='ProsperRating (Alpha)', ylabel='count'>

Employment Status¶

Prosper mainly gave to Clients that were Employed which is one of the ways in which they could effectively try to reduce the Risk of Default in the Portfolio

Text(0, 0.5, 'Employment Status')

Debt To Income Ratio¶

It is a right skewed distribution with most of the customers having relativeliy low debt compared to their income with just few customers breaching the 0.5 ratio mark

Understanding the Relationship between some Quantitave and Qualitative Variables¶

Through the Pair Grid above: the higher the Rating the lower the APR. It could also be noticed that the higher the loan amount the longer the loan tenor in Term. Higher ProsperScore also resulted in Higher Ratings and vice versa. There was a negative correlation between income Ranges and BorrowerAPr, thereby meaninng that the Higher the customer earns the lower the resulting BorrowerAPR. Customer with higher income also opted for higher loan amounts. Finally it seeems Prosper had a rule that the lower the rating the lower the Loan Amount as that is what it seems throught the information plotted above.

<Figure size 1440x1440 with 0 Axes>

Understanding the Realtionship between Borrower APR & Borrower Rate and some other characteristics¶

Unemployed customers generally had higher Rates than other Employment Statuses signaling that unemployed customers actually pose more risk to Prosper. This could also explain why the lower the Rating the higher the BorrowerRate. This could also be amphaiszed as the Rates became considerably lower with rising income. There was also something very noticeable, the higher the BorrowerRate the more likely for the customer to default or for the loan to be chargedoff

The same things noticed when I examined the Borrower Rate is what was noticed when plotted against the BorrowerAPR. This confirms the earlier findings that both are very closely correlated

Text(0, 0.5, 'BorrowerRate')
Text(0, 0.5, 'BorrowerAPR')

Comparing Borrower APR & Income Range with Employment Status to understand how Prosper appraised their loans based on IncomeRange and Employment Status to determine APR¶

Customers that were not employed had a higher BorrowerAPR than the average income earner with common figures of BorrowerAPR above 0.3. Part Time customers had a normally distributed Borrowed APR across the Income Ranges. Higher Income ranges apparently commanded lower Borrower APR.

<Figure size 1440x1440 with 0 Axes>

Comparing Borrower APR, Income Range and Loan Term to determine the relationship between all three variables¶

This supports out thesis that I've been on since that the higher the Income of the individual the lower the Borrower APR. This Facet Grid plot further expantiates on that thesis that it is applicable especially in loan tenors or terms as specified by the data columns. The longer the tenor the lower the Borrower APR as per the higher the income.

<Figure size 1440x1440 with 0 Axes>

Comparing Borrower APR & Income Range with Loan Status To determine the effect of Income and Borrower APR on Loan Status¶

Most of the ChargedOff loans had a higher BorrowerAPR by their mean irregardless of the Income Range in which they were. For currently running loans Customers not employed had a very high BorrowerAPR indicating that they need to be rechecked and visited so as to prevent defaults that will result in writing off such loans.
